{"title": "Dhampyr", "content": "A \"dhampyr\" is a child born of a vampire and a human. They are a prime example of Hybrid Power.\n\nIn vampire folklore, they were said to be normal humans, but would eventually become vampires after death, with the process repeating itself for generations. In modern fiction, they may have all of a vampire's powers and none of their weaknesses, or watered-down versions of both: half as strong but only uncomfortable in sunlight. A stake to the heart is still lethal though \u0097 although, wouldn't a stake to the heart kill you anyway? In some instances (video games especially), holy objects or magic will remain a problem for them even if they are good. Dhampyrs are often vampire hunters and hunters of their own kind. Just as some cultures once believed that murderers and suicides would rise as vampires, a child born approximately nine months after the death of the father might have been accused of this.\n\nIt is more common for the father to be the vampire in this mating since according to folklore, vampire men had far higher sex drives than their female counterparts and were often rapists who targeted human women because they were easy prey. In fiction writing, that is sometimes the case, and other times female vampires are infertile, depending on their degree of deadness. Sometimes avoided altogether by just having a vampire (male or female) bite and turn a pregnant woman (see Blade).\n\nDhampyrs who receive all of a vampire's strengths and none of the weaknesses are at risk of being Mary Sues. When done right, however, they're usually tormented with an uneasy childhood, either because Kids Are Cruel and they're hybrids surrounded by bigots, or because their vampire half is rightly feared by mortals. Of course, that's assuming their vampire parent is around.\n\nThe reason why this word is so different from \"vampire\" is because its etymology is Albanian. Some of the words for this trope in the languages \"vampire\" is derived from (Serbian, Bosnian, Bulgarian, Macedonian) are vampiri\u010d (\u0432\u0430\u043c\u043f\u0438\u0440\u0438\u0447), vampirovi\u010d (\u0432\u0430\u043c\u043f\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447), and vampird\u009ei\u00e2 (\u0432\u0430\u043c\u043f\u0438\u0440\u0434\u0436\u0438\u044f).\n\nSee also I Hate You, Vampire Dad and Lineage Comes from the Father. Contrast Undead Child.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Dhampyr?from=Main.Dhampir", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/Castlevania2017", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/Blade", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/LightNovel/VampireHunterD", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/BloodTheLastVampire", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/TheRecordOfAFallenVampire", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/Karin", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/GhostSweeperMikami", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/BloodyCross", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/VampireKnight", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/JoJosBizarreAdventure", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/LightNovel/Vamp", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/RosarioToVampire", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/MyMonsterSecret", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/VampireKnight", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/LightNovel/TheDeathMageWhoDoesntWantAFourthTime", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/Blade", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/NancyACollins", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/Vampirella", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/AmericanVampire", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/Raptors", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Bloodrayne", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/HotelTransylvania2", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Blade", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Priest2011", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Dracula2000", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/VampireInBrooklyn", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Vamps", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TalesOfAnAncientEmpire", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/Angel", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/KamenRiderKiva", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/TheMunsters", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/LightNovel/VampireHunterD", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/NeilGaiman", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheChroniclesOfVladimirTod", "/pmwiki/p